Add title

Add title to the plot

In[15]:
stocks.plot(title='Selected Stock')
Out[15]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Selected Stock'}, xlabel='date'>

Labeling Plot

Adding labels to the plot.

In[16]:
stocks.plot(title='Stars of Monetization', xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)')
Out[16]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Stars of Monetization'}, xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)'>

Legent setting

Modify / unable legend on the plot.

In[17]:
stocks.plot(title='Stars of Monetization', xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)', legend=False)
Out[17]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Stars of Monetization'}, xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)'>

Colours - customisation

Customise the colour on the plot.

cmpa parameter to set the plot theme on mathplotlib.

https://matplotlib.org/stable/users/explain/colors/colormaps.html

In[18]:
stocks.plot(title='Stars of Monetization', xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)', cmap='Pastel1')
Out[18]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Stars of Monetization'}, xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)'>
In[19]:
stocks.plot(title='Stars of Monetization', xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)', cmap='Accent')
Out[19]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Stars of Monetization'}, xlabel='Time Periods', ylabel='Stock Price ($)'>

Add secondary Y axis

We always can add secondary axis of Y

As below it will be automatically be added to the plot, second syntax row is added ...

In[20]:
stocks['AAPL'].plot()
stocks['IBM'].plot()
Out[20]:
<Axes: xlabel='date'>

I would like separate axis for the IBM

In[21]:
stocks['AAPL'].plot()
stocks['IBM'].plot(secondary_y=True)
Out[21]:
<Axes: >

Size of the graph

Control size of the graph

In[22]:
stocks.plot(figsize=(9, 5))
Out[22]:
<Axes: xlabel='date'>

Subplots

In the example below, I want one single layout with 4 separated plots inside it.

vertical layout

In[23]:
stocks.plot(subplots=True, layout=(1, 4), figsize=(16,6))
Out[23]:
array([[<Axes: xlabel='date'>, <Axes: xlabel='date'>,
        <Axes: xlabel='date'>, <Axes: xlabel='date'>]], dtype=object)

scaling the axes

But , the scale is different for each internal plit.

Let's make the Y axis in the same range:

In[24]:
stocks.plot(subplots=True, layout=(1, 4), figsize=(16,6), sharey=True)
Out[24]:
array([[<Axes: xlabel='date'>, <Axes: xlabel='date'>,
        <Axes: xlabel='date'>, <Axes: xlabel='date'>]], dtype=object)

Horizontal Layout

Range verticallt the subplots:

In[25]:
stocks.plot(subplots=True, layout=(4,1), figsize=(5,10))
Out[25]:
array([[<Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>]], dtype=object)

Let's make all axes the same (shared) for this vertical subplot

In[26]:
stocks.plot(subplots=True, layout=(4,1), figsize=(5,10), sharex=True, sharey=True)
Out[26]:
array([[<Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>]], dtype=object)

grid layout

flexible plot layout. Remember that columns and rows in the grid must match together.

In[27]:
stocks.plot(subplots=True, layout=(2,2), figsize=(8,8))
Out[27]:
array([[<Axes: xlabel='date'>, <Axes: xlabel='date'>],
       [<Axes: xlabel='date'>, <Axes: xlabel='date'>]], dtype=object)
